<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="54" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,152,1376]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,338,1118,1144]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Etymology.</emphasis>
The species epithet derives from the Latin “ 
<taxonomicName box="[860,940,1118,1144]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Villa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="aspros">aspros</taxonomicName>
” means “white diaper”; referring to white scales on the abdomen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="54" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1437,152,1376]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,318,1195,1221]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">Remarks.</emphasis>
The new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Rossi" authorityName="Rossi" box="[668,863,1196,1222]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Villa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="panisca">
<emphasis box="[668,788,1196,1221]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">V. panisca</emphasis>
Rossi
</taxonomicName>
, but it can be separated from the latter by tergites 
<number box="[151,166,1235,1261]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="2.0">2</number>
and 
<number box="[223,238,1235,1261]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="4.0">4</number>
with white recumbent scales anteriorly, tergite 
<number box="[795,810,1235,1261]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="3.0">3</number>
with white recumbent scales antero-laterally, tergites 
<number box="[151,195,1273,1299]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5–6</number>
with white recumbent scales posteriorly; sternite 
<number box="[784,799,1273,1299]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="4.0">4</number>
with the dense white recumbent scales. In 
<taxonomicName box="[1308,1428,1273,1298]" class="Insecta" family="Bombyliidae" genus="Villa" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="panisca">
<emphasis box="[1308,1428,1273,1298]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="54">V. panisca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, tergites 
<number box="[246,261,1312,1338]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="3.0">3</number>
and 
<number box="[321,336,1312,1338]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="4.0">4</number>
have yellow hairs laterally, and tergites 
<number box="[823,867,1312,1338]" pageId="5" pageNumber="54" value="5.5" valueMax="6.0" valueMin="5.0">5–6</number>
have black hair laterally; the sternites have the black erect hairs and yellowish recumbent hairs.
</paragraph>
